<TEXT>
<P>
Soviet citizens and businesses may lease land for 50 years or more, sublease 
the property to others, and pass on the leases to their children when they die 
under a sweeping new law published in Soviet newspapers. The decree, issued by 
the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, creates the same right to lease animals, 
equipment and even entire factories. It grants considerably more extensive 
property rights than many had expected, even after the Communist Party 
leadership in March approved the principle of leasing land to family and 
cooperative farms. The change in Soviet property rights was prompted by the 
disastrous state of the Soviet economy. 
