<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOVIETS GO TO POLLS FOR 2ND TIME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MOSCOW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Soviet voters turned out Sunday for the second time in two weeks to choose 
candidates in 64 constituencies where no clear winners emerged for places in a 
new, more powerful parliament. 
</P>
<P>
The March 26 vote showed public opinion swinging against the Establishment 
across the country, with scores of senior Communist Party and government 
officials failing to win election. 
</P>
<P>
Reformist figures were hoping to seize on the public mood to consolidate their 
gains during the second round, a runoff between the two leaders in 
multi-candidate contests where no one achieved the necessary 50% of the vote. 
Initial results are expected today. 
</P>
<P>
The elections are to a newly created Congress of People's Deputies, which will 
in turn elect from its members a Supreme Soviet (Parliament), endowed with real 
executive powers in contrast to its rubber-stamp predecessor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
